From the Polish team:

{quote}
2) Confluence RSS behaved erratically - typically it just did not work, but sometimes it did. After a couple of hours the problem began to fade and recently everything seems to work fine.
{quote}

I had some problems with the spring plug-in: Assume my spring bean implements the _DisposableBean_ interface. When disabling the spring plugin, the disable event is not propagated to the spring bean instance. So the _destroy_ method is not called. (The enable event is propagated correctly, so in case my spring bean implements _InitializingBean_ the _afterPropertiesSet_ method gets called.) 

I guess the _problem_ is located in the _ConfluenceListableBeanFactory_ class. In case of a spring bean removal the _unregister_ method is called.
{code}
public void unregisterBeanDefinition(String beanAlias)
    {
        registerBeanDefinition(beanAlias, NULL_OBJECT);
        removeSingleton(beanAlias);
    }
{code}

The _removeSingleton_ removes the bean from _AbstractBeanFactory.disposableBeans_ collection without respecting the _DisposableBean_ contract. A solution might be to call _AbstractBeanFactory.destroyBean(..)_ insteat and reverse the order of the method calls in _unregisterBeanDefinition_ , but there might be additional pitfalls. There is some kind of recursive bean destruction in _AbstractBeanFactory_ which could cause some problems.

